<Layout title="Adult Head-to-Toe Examination – Health Assessment">
  <h1>Adult Head-to-Toe Examination</h1>
  <p><em>Health Assessment Component · Section 1: Health Assessment</em></p>
  <p>
    Performing an adult head-to-toe examination requires integration of history taking,
    assessment skills, and communication with the patient.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Learning Objective:</strong> Describe the process of conducting the adult
    head-to-toe examination.
  </p>

  <div class="toc">
    <strong>Sections</strong>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="#seated">Patient Seated</a></li>
      <li><a href="#lying">Patient Lying</a></li>
      <li><a href="#standing">Patient Standing</a></li>
      <li><a href="#functional">Adult Functional Assessment</a></li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── SECTION 1: SEATED ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="seated">Section 1: Patient Seated</h2>

  <h3>Pre-Examination: General Inspection Considerations</h3>
  <p>The physical examination begins with the initial patient encounter. To prepare:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Review the patient's health history — medical, surgical, and family history</li>
    <li>Ask about the chief complaint; think critically about causes; look for related signs and symptoms</li>
    <li>Gather appropriate equipment (stethoscope, vital sign equipment, penlight, gloves, etc.)</li>
    <li>Ensure privacy and comfort (close door, pull curtain, adjust room temperature)</li>
    <li>Record both normal and abnormal findings throughout</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Clinical Pearl</strong>
    The examination should flow smoothly, minimize position changes, and conserve patient energy.
    Modify sequence as needed per patient and situation.
  </div>

  <h3>Steps 1–3: Setup</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Key Points</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>1 — General Inspection</strong></td>
        <td>Begins at initial greeting</td>
        <td>Skin color, facial expression, mobility, dress, posture, speech, orientation, mental alertness</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>2 — Preparation</strong></td>
        <td>Instruct patient to empty bladder, put on gown</td>
        <td>Request chaperone if needed (pelvic/rectal exams)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>3 — Measurements &amp; Vital Signs</strong></td>
        <td>Document all vitals</td>
        <td>Temperature, pulse, respiration, blood pressure, SpO₂</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Steps 4–10: Seated, Wearing Gown</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>4</strong></td>
        <td>Head &amp; Face</td>
        <td>
          Inspect skin; palpate scalp and hair (texture, distribution, quantity);
          palpate facial bones and TMJ; test CN V and VII (clench jaw, squeeze eyes,
          wrinkle forehead, smile, puff cheeks)
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>5</strong></td>
        <td>Eyes</td>
        <td>
          Examine eyelids, lashes, palpebral folds; inspect iris, sclera, conjunctiva;
          test pupillary response (light and accommodation); test extraocular movements
          (CN III, IV, VI); assess visual fields (CN II); ophthalmic exam for red reflex,
          lens, disc, vessels, retinal surfaces
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>6</strong></td>
        <td>Ears</td>
        <td>
          Inspect alignment and surface characteristics; palpate auricle; screen hearing
          with whisper test (CN VIII); Rinne and Weber tests if indicated
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>7</strong></td>
        <td>Nose</td>
        <td>
          Note septum structure and position; determine patency of each nostril;
          inspect mucosa, septum, and turbinates
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>8</strong></td>
        <td>Mouth &amp; Pharynx</td>
        <td>
          Inspect lips, gums, oropharynx, teeth; inspect tongue color, symmetry, movement
          (CN XII); test gag reflex and soft palate (CNs IX and X — ask patient to say "ah")
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>9</strong></td>
        <td>Neck</td>
        <td>
          Inspect and palpate neck and thyroid; test ROM and resistance; shoulder shrug (CN XI);
          palpate carotid pulses (one at a time), tracheal position, thyroid, and lymph nodes;
          auscultate carotid arteries and thyroid
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>10</strong></td>
        <td>Upper Extremities</td>
        <td>
          Inspect skin and nails; inspect symmetry of muscle mass; palpate hands, arms, shoulders;
          assess joint ROM and strength (fingers, wrists, elbows, shoulders);
          assess radial and brachial pulses
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Steps 11–14: Seated, Back and Chest Exposed</h3>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 Note</strong>
    For males: gown pulled down to expose entire chest and back. For females: expose back
    while leaving breasts covered until ready to examine anterior chest.
  </div>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>11</strong></td>
        <td>Back &amp; Posterior Chest</td>
        <td>
          Inspect skin and thorax; inspect shoulder and musculoskeletal symmetry;
          palpate and inspect scapula and spine; palpate/percuss costovertebral angle if indicated
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>12</strong></td>
        <td>Lungs (Posterior)</td>
        <td>
          Observe respirations (depth, rhythm, pattern); palpate for expansion and tactile fremitus;
          palpate scapular/subscapular nodes; percuss posterior chest and lateral walls for resonance;
          percuss diaphragmatic excursion; auscultate systematically for breath sounds
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>13</strong></td>
        <td>Anterior Chest, Lungs &amp; Heart</td>
        <td>
          Inspect skin and musculoskeletal symmetry; palpate chest wall for crepitation and tenderness;
          palpate precordium for thrills, heaves, pulsations; locate apical pulse; palpate tactile fremitus
          and axillary lymph nodes; percuss for resonance; auscultate breath sounds and heart sounds
          (aortic, pulmonic, second pulmonic, mitral, tricuspid)
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>14</strong></td>
        <td>Breasts</td>
        <td>
          <em>Female:</em> Inspect in four positions (arms at sides, arms overhead, hands on hips, leaning forward);
          bimanual digital palpation of breast tissue.
          <em>Male:</em> Inspect for symmetry, enlargement, surface characteristics; palpate breast tissue
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ─── SECTION 2: LYING ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="lying">Section 2: Patient Lying</h2>

  <h3>Step 15: Jugular Assessment (45°)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Assist patient to 45-degree reclining position; stand to the side</li>
    <li>Inspect chest while reclining</li>
    <li>Assess jugular venous distention and jugular pulsations</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 Jugular Pulse</strong>
    A pulsation in the jugular vein caused by conditions that inhibit diastolic filling
    of the right side of the heart.
  </div>

  <h3>Steps 16–20: Supine, Chest and Abdomen Exposed</h3>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 Positioning</strong>
    Assist patient to supine position (30° if unable to lie flat). Uncover chest and abdomen;
    keep lower extremities draped. Inspect abdomen before percussing it.
  </div>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>16</strong></td>
        <td>Female Breast (Supine)</td>
        <td>
          Palpate all areas systematically using light, medium, and deep palpation
          (patient's arm over her head); depress nipple into areola
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>17</strong></td>
        <td>Heart (Supine)</td>
        <td>
          Palpate chest wall for thrills, heaves, pulsations; auscultate systematically;
          may turn patient slightly to left side and repeat
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>18</strong></td>
        <td>Abdomen</td>
        <td>
          Inspect skin, contour, pulsations, and movement; auscultate all quadrants for bowel sounds;
          auscultate aorta and renal, iliac, femoral arteries for bruits; percuss all quadrants;
          percuss liver borders and estimate span; light then deep palpation all quadrants;
          palpate midline for aortic pulsation; assess abdominal muscles (ask patient to raise head)
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>19</strong></td>
        <td>Inguinal Area</td>
        <td>Palpate for lymph nodes, pulses, and hernias</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>20</strong></td>
        <td>External Genitalia (Males)</td>
        <td>
          Inspect penis, urethral meatus, scrotum, and pubic hair;
          palpate scrotal contents; test cremasteric reflex
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Steps 21–23: Supine, Legs Exposed</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>21</strong></td>
        <td>Hips</td>
        <td>Palpate hips for stability; test ROM and strength</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>22</strong></td>
        <td>Legs / Thighs</td>
        <td>Inspect skin characteristics, hair distribution, and muscle mass</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>23</strong></td>
        <td>Feet, Ankles &amp; Knees</td>
        <td>
          Palpate for temperature, texture, edema, and pulses (dorsalis pedis, posterior tibial,
          popliteal); test ROM and strength of toes, feet, ankles, and knees
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Steps 24–27: Female — Lithotomy Position</h3>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 Draping</strong>
    Don gloves; assist patient into lithotomy position; drape appropriately to maintain privacy.
  </div>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>24</strong></td>
        <td>External Genitalia (Females)</td>
        <td>Examine pubic hair, labia, perineum, and anus; palpate labia and Bartholin glands</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>25</strong></td>
        <td>Speculum Examination</td>
        <td>Inspect vagina and cervix; collect specimens if needed</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>26</strong></td>
        <td>Bimanual Palpation</td>
        <td>Assess uterus and cervix</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>27</strong></td>
        <td>Rectal Examination (Female)</td>
        <td>Perform rectovaginal or rectal exam if indicated</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ─── SECTION 3: STANDING ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="standing">Section 3: Patient Standing</h2>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>📌 Safety</strong>
    Stay within arm's reach to assist the patient back to a seated position if necessary.
  </div>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Area</th><th>Assessment Actions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>28</strong></td>
        <td>Spine</td>
        <td>
          Ask patient to bend forward at waist; inspect and palpate spine;
          observe ROM: flexion, hyperextension, lateral bending, rotation of trunk
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>29</strong></td>
        <td>Neurologic Assessment</td>
        <td>
          Observe gait, balance, and proprioception;
          <strong>Romberg test</strong> (feet together, eyes closed);
          walk heel-to-toe; stand on one foot then the other (eyes closed);
          hop in place on one foot then the other;
          assess for inguinal and femoral hernias
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>30</strong></td>
        <td>External Genitalia (Males)</td>
        <td>
          Inspect glans penis, urethral opening, and scrotum;
          palpate scrotum for testes; assess for hernia or hydrocele
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>31</strong></td>
        <td>Rectal Examination (Males)</td>
        <td>
          Patient leans over table (arms/chest resting, toes pointed inward);
          inspect sacrococcygeal and perianal areas; palpate sphincter tone and rectum
          circumferentially for masses; palpate prostate gland; note stool characteristics;
          test for occult blood if indicated
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ─── SECTION 4: FUNCTIONAL ASSESSMENT ─────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="functional">Section 4: Adult Functional Assessment</h2>
  <p>
    Essential for older adult patients; appropriate for any patient limited by disease,
    injury, or disability.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Purpose:</strong> Determine the extent to which Activities of Daily Living
    (ADLs) can be accomplished.
  </p>

  <h3>Components</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Comprehensive history</li>
    <li>Physical examination</li>
    <li>Social assessment</li>
    <li>Detailed medication list (patient-provided)</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Activities of Daily Living</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Basic ADLs</th><th>Instrumental ADLs</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Bathing</td><td>Housekeeping</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dressing</td><td>Grocery shopping</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Toileting</td><td>Meal preparation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ambulation</td><td>Medication management</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Feeding</td><td>Communication skills</td></tr>
      <tr><td></td><td>Money management</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p><em>Also assess use of assistive devices (cane, walker, commode chair, hospital bed).</em></p>

  <h3>System Review — Common Problems in Older Adults</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Nutritional deficiencies and malnutrition</li>
    <li>Urinary incontinence</li>
    <li>Memory changes and signs of dementia</li>
    <li>Depression</li>
    <li>Medication-induced delirium</li>
    <li>Prior falls or fear of falling</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Social Assessment</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Identify current and probable future caregivers; assess abilities and resources</li>
    <li>Assess financial resources and health insurance</li>
    <li>Ask about advance directives or durable power of attorney for health care decisions</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Physical Examination Focus Areas</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>System</th><th>Focus</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Mental status</td><td>Assess cognition, memory, and mood</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Respiratory</td><td>Evaluate for dyspnea on exertion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cardiovascular</td><td>Measure BP sitting and standing — assess for orthostatic hypotension</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Musculoskeletal</td><td>Evaluate strength</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Neurologic</td><td>Pay special attention to balance, coordination, and gait</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Skin</td><td>Inspect for decubitus or venous stasis ulcers</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ─── SUMMARY ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Key Takeaways</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Perform the exam quickly and accurately, maintaining patient comfort throughout</li>
      <li>Some components are best performed <strong>seated</strong>, others while <strong>lying</strong> or <strong>standing</strong></li>
      <li>Structure the sequence based on the <strong>patient's needs</strong>, minimizing position changes</li>
      <li>Perform a <strong>functional assessment when indicated</strong> — especially for older adults or those with functional limitations</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>

